Title:
Tutorial example  - IR photo-electron spectrum of hydrogen

The purpose of this exercise is to explore the calculation of IR spectra
    in linear polarization, learn to assess accuracy and convergence

[TASK] inspect the spectra
[TASK] experiment with TimePropation:fixStep to see effect
[TASK] vary cutEnergy, check impact (larger values require smaller fixStep)
[TASK] perform another calculation with absorption starting only at 30 au
       vary the basis, from comparisons, assess the result
[TASK] increase end time of propagation, see how much spectra are affected
[TASK] set iSurff=false and instead propagate longer, see effect on total spectrum

# TIMING  ~ 12 sec on single CPU  for tRecX + spectral analysis with given parameters
         (results with Intel i7 on laptop)

# plot=total generates total energy spectrum rather than defaul (partial for spherical coordinates)
# iSurff=true indicates that after end of time-propagation the
#             iSurff method for integrating the spectra will be used
#             time propagation needs to proceed to the end of the pulse
#             for now: ONLY for spherically symmetric systems
Spectrum: radialPoints=100, iSurff=true, plot=total

# basis comparatively small, to get results quickly
# nElem...specify number of element (defaults 1), corresponds to nCoefficients=nElem*order
Axis: name,order,nElem,lower end, upper end,functions
 Phi,1
 Eta,19, ,-1,1, assocLegendre{Phi}
 Rn,12, 4, 0.,20.,polynomial
 Rn,20,  , 20.,Infty,polExp[1.]

Absorption: kind, axis, theta, upper
ECS,Rn,0.3,20.

Operator: hamiltonian='1/2<<Laplacian>>-<1><1><trunc[15,20]/Q>'
Operator: interaction='iLaserA0[t]<<D/DZ>>'
Operator: expectationValue='<1><1><chi[0,20]>'

# writes population of field-free states to output and expec files
Occupation: states=0:10, operator=hamiltonian
# note: there is a frequent desire to see the populations
# BUT physical meaning can only be attached to it after the pulse is over
# during the pulse, the values are gauge-dependent

Laser: shape, I(W/cm2), FWHM, lambda(nm)
cos2, 1.e14, 2. OptCyc, 800.

# cutEnergy ...impose a spectral cut on the Hamiltonian
               this essential to speed up up the time-propagation
# fixStep   ...fixed step size for time-stepper (fixStep=0: automatic step size control)
               once known, fixStep>0 may be faster
               find estimate of fixStep: run with fixStep=0 and see "step=..." in outf
TimePropagation: end,print,cutEnergy,accuracy,fixStep
  2 OptCyc, 0.25 OptCyc,30,1e-7,0.045

